article.description:
Tamika Catchings helped avenge Indiana's
lopsided loss to Connecticut that ended the Fever's season.
article.headline: Catchings steals season-high eight
article.linkText: Fever's Catchings steals spotlight, win from Sun
article.story:
INDIANAPOLIS (AP) -- Tamika Catchings helped avenge Indiana's
lopsided loss to Connecticut that ended the Fever's season.

Her all-around performance led the Indiana Fever to a 64-53
victory on Wednesday. Catchings finished with 18 points, nine
rebounds and eight steals -- the most steals by any player this
season.

The Sun (12-4) entered the game with the league's best record,
but that didn't matter to Catchings. What mattered was
Connecticut's 80-60 win on Sept. 19 when the Fever missed the
playoffs and the Sun advanced to the WNBA final.

"I wanted to come out, especially in that second half, and show
that we're a lot different team than we were," she said.

Indiana coach Brian Winters said Catchings made her point.

"What can I say? She's a terrific player," Winters said. "She
fills the box score with numbers and contributes so much that
doesn't show up in the box -- leadership and competitiveness."

The Sun dropped their second game in a row. Indiana improved to
9-6 and solidified its second-place spot behind the Sun in the
Eastern Conference.

Connecticut had won the previous six games against the Fever,
including all four last season.

The Sun led 29-20 at halftime, but Indiana started the second
half with a six-point run to get back into the game.

Indiana finally broke even on a free throw by Catchings, and
took its first lead of the second half at 42-40 on two free throws
by Deanna Jackson.

Indiana forced 24 turnovers, including 15 in the second half.
Connecticut guard Katie Douglas said the Fever effectively
frustrated the Sun's guards. Teammate Lindsay Whalen finished with
three points and four assists.

"That seemed to be their game plan," she said. "We didn't
execute ours. It's uncharacteristic of us to not take care of the
ball. That is huge for us."

"Give Indiana credit," said Connecticut coach Mike Thibault.
"They hustled."

Indiana's Kelly Miller scored 11 of her 15 points in the second
half, and Jackson scored all 11 of hers after the break.

Indiana shot 25 percent in the first half, but better than 50
percent after the break.

Nykesha Sales led Connecticut with 15 points. Taj
McWilliams-Franklin added 14 points and Douglas 11 for the Sun.

Connecticut, the league's highest-scoring team, was held to a
season-low point total.
